✨ Understanding the game:¶

Baseball, Game played with a bat and ball between two teams of nine players (or 10, if a designated hitter bats and runs for the pitcher). Baseball is played on a large field that has four bases laid out in a square, positioned like a diamond, whose outlines mark the course a runner must take to score.

The "_ fielder" positions are called outer field positions and the rest are inner field.

Descriptive statistics summary 📝:¶

✨ Overview:¶

The given data set has 352 entries. Out of the 21 variables, 19 of them are neumerical variables and 2 (race & position) are categrorical.

✨ Takeways:¶

  1. Intuitively Salary would depend on the performance of the player and not the other way around. And most variables are about the performance of the individual players. We will run our regression on this dependent variable later on.
  2. Data seems skewed so we might need to do log transformations before conducting statistical tests
  3. The distribution of data over the catagorical variables are uneven. We have to be careful while maing comparative studies.
  4. There are some missing data we will handle them in the next section.

✨ Why we need to normalize?¶

Since we have unequal numbers of observations, comparing their distributions in terms of counts may not be ideal. One solution is to normalize the counts using the stat parameter. the normalization is applied to the entire distribution, so this simply rescales the height of the bars. By setting common_norm=False, each subset will be normalized independently.

✨ General statements:¶

  1. Outfield: its comparitively more common for a black players to play this position
  2. Catcher, outfield: its comparitively more common for a white players to play these position
  3. Shortstop, outfield: its played by both white and hispanic players
Secondary research shows that shortstop is an "action-packed" position and the most agile players are placed here. If we assume the stereotype that hispanics and whites are agile, the data stays coherent with the research statement.¶
Catchers position is assumed to be the hardest, the whites dominate this position among other races¶
The outfield positions are generally considered to be easier to play than the infield positions and tend to be dominated by good hitters. And as the data shows, the outfield is dominated by the blacks, but other races are there as well.¶

🤔 This begs the question: Are all outfields good hitters? Is this statement statistically significant?¶

📉 Statements about the last few graphs¶

  1. Its comparitively more probable for hispanics to hit less than 100 homeruns.
  2. Its comparitively more probable for hispanics to get more striked outs.
  3. For home runs and career walks, both the distributions are right skewed. Some outlier values are there, meaning some people are outperforming others in these aspects. The graph shows that these are mostly blacks and some are whites.

Secondary research on these statements:¶

Secondary research confirms this last statement that blacks are comparitively morelikely to be atheletically gifted, so they are the big hitters. Although most of the heavy hitters are white but that might be because baseball itself is a very "white" centered game, number of white players are comparitively higher.

Extending on the hispanics 🌮:¶

Hispanics are comparitively underperforming but they are still prevelant in the sport. Presumeably because of 2 reasons:

A. Agility: Hispanics are comparitively shorter and they outperform others with their positioning and faster reflexes in important positions of the field. (Probably thats why they were more common in the "shortstop position" which is known to be one of the hardest positions to play)

B. Exposure: The alternative sports in America are basketball and football, both of which require genetically gifted physique to have an upperhand. So its safe to assume hispanics are comfortable choosing a sport where they know they will be able to contibute substantially.

We will conduct our test with crosstb1 because chi-square doesnt assume normalized data.

🧪 Chi-squared testing:¶

Null hypothesis: There is no relation between the race and player position.

Alternate hypothesis: There is significant relation between the race and player position.

Significance level (): 0.05

In [ ]:
chi2, p_val, dof, expected =stats.chi2_contingency(crosstb1)

print(f'chi2: {chi2}')
print(f'dof: {dof}')
print(f'expected: {expected}')

Comments on Chi-squared¶

P value is below .05 so we can reject the null. There is significant relationship between the 2 catagorical variables.

Expected values differ from observed values:

  1. Among 52 catchers only 2 are black. Statistically expected 16 black people to be catchers. 43 of the catchers are white, double of what it was expected to be. This position is dominated by black people

  2. Among 136 outfielders only 72 are black (More than half of the outfielders are black). Statistically expected 41 black people to be outfielders. 45 of the outfielders are white, whereas it was expected to be 69 white outfielders. This position is dominated by white people

  3. Among 49 shortstoppers only 7 are black. Statistically expected 15 black people to be shortstoppers. 19 of the shortstoppers are hispanic, whereas it was expected to be 9 hispanic shortstoppers. This position is dominated by hispanic people

Takeaway:¶

Whites over represent the Catchers position

Blacks over represent the Outfielders position

Hispanics over represent the Shortstoppers position

🔮 Hypothesis testing: Null and alternate hypothesis¶

We used 2 populations a)black players, b)white players; both these populations are farther filtered by their career runs. Both of the populations are in the same career runs range.

The two hypotheses for this two sample t-test are as follows:

  1. H0: 1 = 2 (the two population means are equal)

  2. HA: 1 2 (the two population means are not equal)

In [ ]:
test_black = black[(black['career_runs']>=400) & (black['career_runs']<=1500)]['salary']
test_black.mean()
Out[ ]:
3089273.611111111
In [ ]:
stat, p = levene(test_black, test_white)
p
Out[ ]:
0.5747528285484527

We p value is > than .05 so we can assume equal variance.

In [ ]:
t_val, p_val = stats.ttest_ind(test_black,test_white, equal_var=True)
print(f"t-value: {t_val}, p_value:{p_val}")

t-value: 1.7260085055910541, p_value:0.08851920540864197

✨ Interpretation of the t-test:¶

Because the p-value of our test (0.08851920540864197) is greater than alpha = 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis of the test. We do not have sufficient evidence to say that the mean salary between the two populations is different.

Within the same career runs range, black and white players salaries dont differ in any statistically significant manner. According to the data their is no apparent wage gap.

7.2. T-test on subsets of data¶

Lets see if the outfielders are really better hitters or not.¶

🔮 Hypothesis testing: Null and alternate hypothesis¶

We used 2 populations a)Outfield players, b)Not outfield players; We will see if the means of career runs of these 2 subsets are significantly different or not.

The two hypotheses for this two sample t-test are as follows:

  1. H0: 1 = 2 (the two population means are equal)

  2. HA: 1 2 (the two population means are not equal)

In [ ]:
heavyhitters_outfield = df[df['player_position'] == "outfield"]['career_runs']
heavyhitters_outfield.mean()
Out[ ]:
339.1029411764706
In [ ]:
heavyhitters_others = df[df['player_position'] != "outfield"]['career_runs']
heavyhitters_others.mean()
Out[ ]:
256.10185185185185
In [ ]:
t_val, p_val = stats.ttest_ind(heavyhitters_outfield, heavyhitters_others)
print(f't-value: {t_val},p-value: {p_val}')

t-value: 2.560197819591747,p-value: 0.01088046513395104

✨ Interpretation of the t-test:¶

Because the p-value of our test (0.01088046513395104) is lower than alpha = 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis of the test. We have sufficient evidence to say that the mean career runs of these two are statistically significant.

In simple words:¶

  • Outfielders are definitely better run scorers than the others.

🔬 Interpretation of regression:¶

Salary, (y) = 10.6262 + 0.4235(career_runs) + 0.2403(career_homeruns)

The equation values are log transformed.

If the career runs increase by 1 then the salary increases by 0.4235(units log transformed), if career_homeruns increases by 1 unit then salary increases by 0.2403 units.

Takeaways:¶

  1. 63% of the data can be explained through this model
  2. There is significant relationship between independent and dependent variables as the significane F clears
  3. The predicting variables are good as the p values are below .05, the model is parsimonious.
  4. There are no multi-collinearity issues in our model
  • Hitting homeruns, getting more runs increases the salary.
